We first solve the indefinite integral, using the trigonometric identity
$\sin(2x) = 2\sin(x)\cos(x)$:

\begin{align*}
\int \sin(\pi x)\cos(\pi x)\,dx &= \int \frac12 \sin(2\pi x)\,dx \\
&=-\frac1{4\pi}\cos(2\pi x) + C. 
\end{align*}

Therefore

\begin{align*}
I_1 &= \int_{1/2}^1 \sin(\pi x)\cos(\pi x)\,dx \\
&= \left.\frac{-1}{4\pi}\cos(2\pi x)\right|_{1/2}^1 \\
&= \frac{-1}{4\pi} \cos(2\pi) + \frac1{4\pi} \cos(\pi) \\
&= -\frac1{4\pi} - \frac1{4\pi}= -\frac1{2\pi}. 
\end{align*}
